Usage: nmcli general hostname { ARGUMENTS | help }
ARGUMENTS := [<hostname>]
Get or change persistent system hostname. With no arguments, this prints currently configured hostname. When you pass a hostname, NetworkManager will set it as the new persistent system hostname.

Usage: nmcli general hostname { ARGUMENTS | help }
ARGUMENTS := [<hostname>]
Get or change persistent system hostname. With no arguments, this prints currently configured hostname. When you pass a hostname, NetworkManager will set it as the new persistent system hostname.

Usage: nmcli general logging { ARGUMENTS | help }
ARGUMENTS := [level <log level>] [domains <log domains>]
Get or change NetworkManager logging level and domains. Without any argument current logging level and domains are shown. In order to change logging state, provide level and/or domain. Please refer to the man page for the list of possible logging domains.

Usage: nmcli general logging { ARGUMENTS | help }
ARGUMENTS := [level <log level>] [domains <log domains>]
Get or change NetworkManager logging level and domains. Without any argument current logging level and domains are shown. In order to change logging state, provide level and/or domain. Please refer to the man page for the list of possible logging domains.

Usage: nmcli general status { help }

Show overall status of NetworkManager.
'status' is the default action, which means 'nmcli gen' calls 'nmcli gen status'

Usage: nmcli general status { help }

Show overall status of NetworkManager.
'status' is the default action, which means 'nmcli gen' calls 'nmcli gen status'

Usage: nmcli networking connectivity { ARGUMENTS | help }
ARGUMENTS := [check]
Get network connectivity state. The optional 'check' argument makes NetworkManager re-check the connectivity.

Usage: nmcli networking connectivity { ARGUMENTS | help }
